# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: digital-audio-workstation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] In sound recording and reproduction, **audio mixing** is the process of optimizing and combining multitrack recordings into a final mono, stereo or surround sound product.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] In the process of combining the separate tracks, their relative levels are adjusted and balanced and various processes such as equalization and compression are commonly applied to individual tracks, groups of tracks, and the overall mix.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] In stereo and surround sound mixing, the placement of the tracks within the stereo (or surround) field are adjusted and balanced.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] Audio mixing techniques and approaches vary widely and have a significant influence on the final product.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] Audio mixing techniques largely depend on music genres and the quality of sound recordings involved.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] The process is generally carried out by a mixing engineer, though sometimes the record producer or recording artist may assist.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] After mixing, a mastering engineer prepares the final product for production.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] Audio mixing may be performed on a mixing console or in a digital audio workstation.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] In the late 19th century, Thomas Edison and Emile Berliner developed the first recording machines.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] The recording and reproduction process itself was completely mechanical with little or no electrical parts.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] Edison's phonograph cylinder system utilized a small horn terminated in a stretched, flexible diaphragm attached to a stylus which cut a groove of varying depth into the malleable tin foil of the cylinder.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] Emile Berliner's gramophone system recorded music by inscribing spiraling lateral cuts onto a vinyl disc.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] Electronic recording became more widely used during the 1920s.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] It was based on the principles of electromagnetic transduction.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] The possibility for a microphone to be connected remotely to a recording machine meant that microphones could be positioned in more suitable places.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] The process was improved when outputs of the microphones could be mixed before being fed to the disc cutter, allowing greater flexibility in the balance.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] Before the introduction of multitrack recording, all sounds and effects that were to be part of a recording were mixed simultaneously during a live performance.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] If the recorded mix was not satisfactory, or if one musician made a mistake, the selection had to be performed over until the desired balance and performance was obtained.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] The introduction of multi-track recording changed the recording process into one that generally involves three stages: recording, overdubbing, and mixing.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] Modern mixing emerged with the introduction of commercial multi-track tape machines, most notably when 8-track recorders were introduced during the 1960s.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] The ability to record sounds into separate channels made it possible for recording studios to combine and treat these sounds not only during recording, but afterward during a separate mixing process.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] The introduction of the cassette-based Portastudio in 1979 offered multi-track recording and mixing technology that did not require the specialized equipment and expense of commercial recording studios.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] Bruce Springsteen recorded his 1982 album *Nebraska* with one, and the Eurythmics topped the charts in 1983 with the song "Sweet Dreams (Are Made of This)", recorded by band member Dave Stewart on a makeshift 8-track recorder.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] In the mid-to-late 1990s, computers replaced tape-based recording for most home studios, with the Power Macintosh proving popular.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] In the mid-1980s, many professional recording studios began to use digital audio workstations (DAWs) to accomplish recording and mixing previously done with multitrack tape recorders, mixing consoles, and outboard gear.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] A mixer (mixing console, mixing desk, mixing board, or software mixer) is the operational heart of the mixing process.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] Mixers offer a multitude of inputs, each fed by a track from a multitrack recorder.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] Mixers typically have 2 main outputs (in the case of two-channel stereo mixing) or 8 (in the case of surround).
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] Mixers offer three main functionalities.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] Routing of source signals to internal buses or external processing units and effects.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] On-board processors with equalizers and compressors.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] Mixing consoles can be large and intimidating due to the exceptional number of controls.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] However, because many of these controls are duplicated (e.g. per input channel), much of the console can be learned by studying one small part of it.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] The controls on a mixing console will typically fall into one of two categories: processing and configuration.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] Processing controls are used to manipulate the sound.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] These can vary in complexity, from simple level controls, to sophisticated outboard reverberation units.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] Configuration controls deal with the signal routing from the input to the output of the console through the various processes.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] Digital audio workstations (DAW) can perform many mixing features in addition to other processing.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] An audio control surface gives a DAW the same user interface as a mixing console.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] Outboard audio processing units (analog) and software-based audio plug-ins (digital) are used for each track or group to perform various processing techniques.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] These processes, such as equalization, compression, sidechaining, stereo imaging, and saturation are used to make each element as audible and sonically appealing as possible.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] The mix engineer also will use such techniques to balance the *space* of the final audio wave; removing unnecessary frequencies and volume spikes to minimize the interference or *clashing* between each element.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] The frequency response of a signal represents the amount (volume) of every frequency in the human hearing range, consisting of (on average) frequencies from 20 Hz to 20,000 Hz (20 kHz.) There are a variety of processes commonly used to edit frequency response in various ways.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] The mixdown process converts a program with a multiple-channel configuration into a program with fewer channels.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] Common examples include downmixing from 5.1 surround sound to stereo, and stereo to mono.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] Because these are common scenarios, it is common practice to verify the sound of such downmixes during the production process to ensure stereo and mono compatibility.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] The alternative channel configuration can be explicitly authored during the production process with multiple channel configurations provided for distribution.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] For example, on DVD-Audio or Super Audio CD, a separate stereo mix can be included along with the surround mix.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] Alternatively, the program can be automatically downmixed by the end consumer's audio system.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] For example, a DVD player or sound card may downmix a surround sound program to stereo for playback through two speakers.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] Any console with a sufficient number of mix busses can be used to create a 5.1 surround sound mix, but this may be frustrating if the console is not specifically designed to facilitate signal routing, panning, and processing in a surround sound environment.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] Whether working in an analog hardware, digital hardware, or DAW mixing environment, the ability to pan mono or stereo sources and place effects in the 5.1 soundscape and monitor multiple output formats without difficulty can make the difference between a successful or compromised mix.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] Mixing in surround is very similar to mixing in stereo except that there are more speakers, placed to *surround* the listener.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] In addition to the horizontal panoramic options available in stereo, mixing in surround lets the mix engineer pan sources within a much wider and more enveloping environment.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] In a surround mix, sounds can appear to originate from many more or almost any direction depending on the number of speakers used, their placement and how audio is processed.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] There are two common ways to approach mixing in surround.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] Naturally, these approaches can be combined in any way the mix engineer sees fit.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] Recently, a third approach to mixing in surround was developed by surround mix engineer Unne Liljeblad.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] An extension to surround sound is 3D sound, used by formats such as Dolby Atmos.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] Known as *object-based* sound, this enables additional speakers to represent height channels, with as many as 64 unique speaker feeds.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-mixing-recorded-music] This has application in concert recordings, movies and videogames, and nightclub events.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-plug-in] In computer software, an **audio plug-in** is a plug-in that can add or enhance audio-related functions in a computer program, typically a digital audio workstation.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-plug-in] Such functions may include digital signal processing or sound synthesis.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-plug-in] Audio plug-ins usually provide their own user interface, which often contains graphical user interface (GUI) widgets that can be used to control and visualize the plug-in's audio parameters.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-plug-in] There are three broad classes of audio plug-in: those which transform existing audio samples, those which generate new audio samples through sound synthesis, and those which analyze existing audio samples.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-plug-in] Although all plug-in types can technically perform audio analysis, only specific formats provide a mechanism for analysis data to be returned to the host.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-plug-in] The program used to dynamically load audio plug-ins is called a plug-in host.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-plug-in] Example hosts include Bidule, Gig Performer, Mainstage, REAPER, and Sonic Visualiser.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-plug-in] Plug-ins can also be used to host other plug-ins.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-plug-in] Communication between host and plug-in(s) is determined by a plug-in application programming interface (API).
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-plug-in] The API declares functions and data structures that the plug-in must define to be usable by a plug-in host.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-plug-in] Additionally, a functional specification may be provided, which defines how the plug-in should respond to function calls, and how the host should expect to handle function calls to the plug-in.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-plug-in] The specification may also include documentation about the meaning of variables and data structures declared in the API.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/audio-plug-in] The API header files, specification, shared libraries, license, and documentation are sometimes bundled together in a software development kit (SDK).
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] A **digital audio workstation** (**DAW** /dɔː/) is an electronic device or application software used for recording, editing and producing audio files.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] DAWs come in a wide variety of configurations, from a single software program on a laptop, to an integrated stand-alone unit, all the way to a highly complex configuration of numerous components controlled by a central computer.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] Regardless of configuration, modern DAWs have a central interface that allows the user to alter and mix multiple recordings and tracks into a final produced piece.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] DAWs are used for producing and recording music, songs, speech, radio, television, soundtracks, podcasts, sound effects and nearly every other kind of complex recorded audio.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] Early attempts at digital audio workstations in the 1970s and 1980s faced limitations such as the high price of storage and the vastly slower processing and disk speeds of the time.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] In 1978, Soundstream, who had made one of the first commercially available digital audio tape recorders in 1977, built what could be considered the first digital audio workstation using some of the most current computer hardware of the time.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] Interface cards that plugged into the PDP-11's Unibus slots (the Digital Audio Interface, or DAI) provided analog and digital audio input and output for interfacing to Soundstream's digital recorders and conventional analog tape recorders.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] The DAP software could perform edits to the audio recorded on the system's hard disks and produce simple effects such as crossfades.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] By the late 1980s, a number of personal computers such as the Macintosh, Atari ST, and Amiga began to have enough power to handle digital audio editing.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] Engineers used Macromedia's Soundedit, with Microdeal's Replay Professional and Digidesign's *Sound Tools* and *Sound Designer* to edit audio samples for sampling keyboards like the E-mu Emulator II and the Akai S900.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] Soon, people began to use them for simple two-track audio editing and audio mastering.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] In 1989, Sonic Solutions released the first professional (48 kHz at 24 bit) disk-based non-linear audio editing system.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] The Macintosh IIfx-based Sonic System, based on research done earlier at George Lucas' Sprocket Systems, featured complete CD premastering, with integrated control of Sony's industry-standard U-matic tape-based digital audio editor.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] Many major recording studios switched over to using digital audio after Digidesign introduced its Pro Tools software in 1991, modeled after the traditional method and signal flow in most analog recording devices.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] At this time, most DAWs were Apple Mac based (e.g., Pro Tools, Studer Dyaxis, Sonic Solutions).
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] Around 1992, the first Windows-based DAWs started to emerge from companies such as Innovative Quality Software (IQS) (now SAWStudio), Soundscape Digital Technology, SADiE, Echo Digital Audio, and Spectral Synthesis.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] All the systems at this point used dedicated hardware for their audio processing.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] In 1992, Sunrize Industries released the AD516 soundcard for big-box Amiga computers.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] This allowed up to 8 tracks of 16-bit 48 kHz direct-to-disk recording and playback using its Studio 16 software.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] It could also integrate directly into Blue Ribbon Soundworks' Bars & Pipes Pro MIDI software or NewTek's Video Toaster, thus providing a complete package of MIDI sequencing and/or video synchronization with non-linear hard disk recording.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] In 1993, the German company Steinberg released Cubase Audio on Atari Falcon 030.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] This version brought DSP built-in effects with 8-track audio recording and playback using only native hardware.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] The first Windows-based software-only product, introduced in 1993, was Samplitude (which already existed in 1992 as an audio editor for the Commodore Amiga).
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] An integrated DAW consists of a digital signal processing, control surface, audio converters, and data storage in one device.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] Integrated DAWs were popular before commonly available personal computers became powerful enough to run DAW software.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] As personal computer power and speed increased and prices decreased, the popularity of costly integrated systems dropped.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] DAW can refer to the software itself, but traditionally, a computer-based DAW has four basic components: a computer, a sound card or other audio interface, audio editing software, and at least one user input device for adding or modifying data.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] This could be as simple as a mouse and keyboard or as sophisticated as a piano-style MIDI controller keyboard or automated audio control surface for mixing track volumes.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] The computer acts as a host for the sound card, while the software provides the interface and functionality for audio editing.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] The sound card typically converts analog audio signals into a digital form, and digital back to analog audio when playing it back; it may also assist in further processing of the audio.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] The software controls all related hardware components and provides a user interface to allow for recording, editing, and playback.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] Computer-based DAWs have extensive recording, editing, and playback capabilities (and some also have video-related features).
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] For example, they can provide a practically limitless number of tracks to record on, polyphony, and virtual synthesizers or sample-based instruments to use for recording music.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] DAWs can also provide a wide variety of effects, such as reverb, to enhance or change the sounds themselves.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] Simple smartphone-based DAWs, called mobile audio workstations (MAWs), are used (for example) by journalists for recording and editing on location.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] As software systems, DAWs are designed with many user interfaces, but generally, they are based on a multitrack tape recorder metaphor, making it easier for recording engineers and musicians already familiar with using tape recorders to become familiar with the new systems.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] Therefore, computer-based DAWs tend to have a standard layout that includes transport controls (play, rewind, record, etc.), track controls and a mixer.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] A waveform display is another common feature.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] Single-track DAWs display only one (mono or stereo form) track at a time.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] Multitrack DAWs support operations on multiple tracks at once.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] Like a mixing console, each track typically has controls that allow the user to adjust the gain, equalization and stereo panning of the sound on each track.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] In a traditional recording studio, additional rackmount processing gear is physically plugged into the audio signal path to add reverb, compression, etc.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] However, a DAW can also route in software or use audio plug-ins (for example, a VST plugin) to process the sound on a track.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] Perhaps the most significant feature available from a DAW that is not available in analog recording is the ability to undo a previous action, using a command similar to that of the undo function in word processing software.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] Undo makes it much easier to avoid accidentally permanently erasing or recording over a previous recording.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] If a mistake or unwanted change is made, the undo command is used to conveniently revert the changed data to a previous state.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] Cut, Copy, Paste, and Undo are familiar and common computer commands and they are usually available in DAWs in some form.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] More common functions include the modifications of several factors concerning a sound.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] These include wave shape, pitch, tempo, and filtering.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] Commonly, DAWs feature some form of mix automation using procedural line segment-based or curve-based interactive graphs.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] The lines and curves of the automation graph are joined by or comprise adjustable points.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] By creating and adjusting multiple points along a waveform or control events, the user can specify parameters of the output over time (e.g., volume or pan).
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] Automation data may also be directly derived from human gestures recorded by a control surface or MIDI controller.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] MIDI recording, editing, and playback is increasingly incorporated into modern DAWs of all types, as is synchronization with other audio or video tools.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] There are many free and open-source software programs that perform DAW functions.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] These are designed to run on a variety of operating systems and are usually developed non-commercially.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] Personal Composer, created by Jim Miller for Yamaha, was the star of the NAMM Show in 1983.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] Personal Composer runs under MS DOS 2.0 and includes a MIDI sequencer, synth editor (such as Yamaha's DX7), universal librarians and a score editor.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] The software was later released as Personal Composer System/2 (1988).
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] Cubase not only modeled a tape-like interface for recording and editing, but, in addition, using VST, also developed by Steinberg, modeled the entire mixing desk and effects rack common in analog studios.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] This revolutionized the DAW world, both in features and price tag, and was quickly imitated by most other contemporary DAW systems.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] Digital audio applications for Linux and BSD fostered technologies such as Advanced Linux Sound Architecture (ALSA), which drives audio hardware, and JACK Audio Connection Kit.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] JACK allows any JACK-aware audio software to connect to any other audio software running on the system, such as connecting an ALSA- or OSS-driven soundcard to a mixing and editing front-end, like Ardour or Rosegarden.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] In this way, JACK acts as a virtual audio patch bay, and it can be configured to use a computer's resources in real time, with dedicated memory, and with various options that minimize the DAW's latency.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] This kind of abstraction and configuration allows DJs to use multiple programs for editing and synthesizing audio streams, or multitasking and duplexing, without the need for analog conversion, or asynchronous saving and reloading files, and ensures a high level of audio fidelity.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] Members of the Linux Audio Development (LAD) mailing list have contributed to the development of standards such as the LADSPA, DSSI and LV2 plugin architectures.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] The Virtual Studio Technology (VST) plugin standard is supported by some programs.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] There are countless software plugins for DAW software, each one coming with its own unique functionality, thus expanding the overall variety of sounds and manipulations that are possible.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] Each has their own form of generating or manipulating sound, tone, pitch, and speed of a simple sound and transforming it into something different.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] To achieve an even more distinctive sound, multiple plugins can be used in layers and further automated to manipulate the original sounds.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] Recent developments in generative artificial intelligence are changing DAW software.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] A research paper from Georgia Tech, titled "Composing with Generative Systems in the Digital Audio Workstation", proposed the term *Generative Audio Workstation* to describe this new class of DAWs.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] Three examples of notable GAWs are AIVA, WavTool, and Symphony V.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] AIVA provides parameter-based AI MIDI song generation within a DAW.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] WavTool offers a browser DAW equipped with a GPT-4 composition assistant and AI text-to-sample generator.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] Symphony V provides generative vocal synthesis, note editing, and mixing tools.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] Generative AI services have also become available through plugins that integrate with conventional DAWs, such as Izotope Neutron 4, TAIP, and Synthesizer V.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] Neutron 4 includes a *mix assistant* that uses machine learning to analyze audio and automatically apply processing effects.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] TAIP provides tape saturation powered by AI neural networks that imitate traditional DSP processing.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] Synthesizer V offers several AI vocalists whose notes can be manipulated.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] To reduce the strain on computer memory, some plugin companies have developed thin client VSTs that use resources from a cloud server.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] For example, the audio-to-MIDI plugin Samplab offers a desktop application with user authentication and API calls that perform stem separation and MIDI transcription off of the computer's local device.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] This can improve load speeds or prevent applications from crashing.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] DAWs can be implemented in a music education class to show students how to use them and learn how to produce their own music.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] According to a study done by the Indonesia University of Education, the use of a DAW in music learning can let students build their learning of music production on their own.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] Another study done by the University of Milan made a DAW accessible to kids.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] The usage of DAW can be found in most hip hop and EDM music with the use of looping an instrumental.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/digital-audio-workstation] With music production also moving to a laptop, music making has shifted from professional studios and into bedrooms.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] A multitrack recorder allows one or more sound sources to be simultaneously recorded to different tracks, which may subsequently be processed and mixed separately.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] The singer's microphone, the output of the guitars and keys, and each individual drum in the kit can all be recorded separately using a multitrack recorder.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] This allows each track to be fine-tuned individually, such as increasing the voice or lowering the chimes, before combining them into the final product.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Prior to the development of multitracking, the sound recording process required all of the singers, band instrumentalists, and/or orchestra accompanists to perform at the same time in the same space.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Multitrack recording was a significant technical improvement as it allowed studio engineers to record all of the instruments and vocals for a piece of music separately.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Multitracking allowed the engineer to adjust the levels and tone of each individual track, and if necessary, redo certain tracks or overdub parts of the track to correct errors or get a better *take*.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Also, different electronic effects such as reverb could be applied to specific tracks, such as the lead vocals, while not being applied to other tracks where this effect would not be desirable (e.g., on the electric bass).
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] In the 1980s and 1990s, computers provided means by which both sound recording and reproduction could be digitized, revolutionizing audio recording and distribution.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] In the 2000s, multitracking hardware and software for computers was of sufficient quality to be widely used for high-end audio recordings by both professional sound engineers and by bands recording without studios using widely available programs, which can be used on a high-end laptop computer.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Though magnetic tape has not been replaced as a recording medium, the advantages of non-linear editing (NLE) and recording have resulted in digital systems largely superseding tape.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Even in the 2010s, with digital multitracking being the dominant technology, the original word *track* is still used by audio engineers.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Multi-track recording devices vary in their specifications, such as the number of simultaneous tracks available for recording at any one time; in the case of tape-based systems, this is limited by, among other factors, the physical size of the tape employed.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] With the introduction of SMPTE timecode in the early 1970s, engineers began to use computers to perfectly synchronize separate audio and video playback, or multiple audio tape machines.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] In this system, one track of each machine carried the timecode synchronization signal.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Over the years, the industry transitioned from 16-track to 24-track recording on 2-inch tape to twin 24-tracks for 48-track recording (up to 46 audio tracks).
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] An extreme example of this occurred in 1982, when the rock group Toto recorded parts of *Toto IV* on three synchronized 24-track machines.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] This setup allowed for 66 audio tracks, using track 24 of each machine for time code, and leaving track 23 unused to prevent interference with the audio.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] In the late 1970s and 1980s, digital multitrack tape machines emerged, including the 3M and Mitsubishi X-800 32-track machines, and Sony DASH PCM-3324 and later the PCM-3348 machines, which allowed greater flexibility with more available tracks for recording.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] As well, in order to mix using automation on the console, analogue recorders generally required adjacent tracks to the time code track to be kept blank to avoid the time code signal interfering with the audio signals, which limited available tracks to 22 or 23 track at most.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Digital multitrack machines had time code inserted elsewhere on the tape, and thus did not require allocating it to an audio track, which meant all tracks were available for recording.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] What's more, in the case of the PCM-3348, which doubled the number of tracks from the PCM-3324, both machines could use the same ½” digital tape, and also a 24-track reel first recorded on a PCM-3324 was able to be used on a PCM-3348 and have another 24 tracks overdubbed.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] For computer-based systems, the trend in the 2000s is towards unlimited numbers of record/playback tracks, although issues such as RAM memory and CPU available do limit this from machine to machine.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Moreover, on computer-based systems, the number of simultaneously available recording tracks is limited by the number of sound card discrete analog or digital inputs.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] When recording, audio engineers can select which track (or tracks) on the device will be used for each instrument, voice, or other input and can even blend one track with two instruments to vary the music and sound options available.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] At any given point on the tape, any of the tracks on the recording device can be recording or playing back using sel-sync or Selective Synchronous recording.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] This allows an artist to be able to record onto track 2 and, simultaneously, listen to tracks 1, 3 and 7, allowing them to sing or to play an accompaniment to the performance already recorded on these tracks.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] They might then record an alternate version on track 4 while listening to the other tracks.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] All the tracks can then be played back in perfect synchrony, as if they had originally been played and recorded together.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] This can be repeated until all of the available tracks have been used, or in some cases, reused.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] During mixdown, a separate set of playback heads with higher fidelity are used.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Before all tracks are filled, any number of existing tracks can be *bounced* into one or two tracks, and the original tracks erased, making more room for more tracks to be reused for fresh recording.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] In 1963, the Beatles were using twin track for *Please Please Me*.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] The Beatles' producer George Martin used this technique extensively to achieve multiple-track results, while still being limited to using only multiple four-track machines, until an eight-track machine became available during the recording of the Beatles' self-titled ninth album.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] The Beach Boys' *Pet Sounds* also made innovative use of multitracking with eight-track machines of the day (circa 1965).
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Motown also began recording with eight-track machines in 1965, before moving to 16-track machines in mid-1969.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Multitrack recording also allows any recording artist to record multiple *takes* of any given section of their performance, allowing them to refine their performance to virtual perfection by making additional *takes* of songs or instrumental tracks.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] A recording engineer can record only the section being worked on, without erasing any other section of that track.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] This process of turning the recording mechanism on and off is called punching in and punching out.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] When recording is completed, the many tracks are *mixed down* through a mixing console to a two-track stereo recorder in a format which can then be duplicated and distributed.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Most of the records, CDs and cassettes commercially available in a music store are recordings that were originally recorded on multiple tracks, and then mixed down to stereo.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] In some rare cases, as when an older song is technically *updated*, these stereo (or mono) mixes can in turn be recorded (as if it were a *submix*) onto two (or one) tracks of a multitrack recorder, allowing additional sound (tracks) to be layered on the remaining tracks.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] During multitracking, multiple musical instruments (and vocals) can be recorded, either one at a time or simultaneously, onto individual tracks, so that the sounds thus recorded can be accessed, processed and manipulated individually to produce the desired results.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] In the 2010s, many rock and pop bands recorded each part of the song one after the other.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] First, the bass and drums are often recorded, followed by the chordal rhythm section instruments.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Then the lead vocals and guitar solos are added.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] As a last step, the harmony vocals are added.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] On the other hand, orchestras are always recorded with all 70 to 100 instrumentalists playing their parts simultaneously.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] If each group of instruments has its own microphone, and each instrument with a solo melody has its own microphone, the different microphones can record on multiple tracks simultaneously.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] After recording the orchestra, the record producer and conductor can adjust the balance and tone of the different instrument sections and solo instruments, because each section and solo instrument was recorded to its own track.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] With the rock or pop band example, after recording some parts of a song, an artist might listen to *only* the guitar part by *muting* all the tracks except the one on which the guitar was recorded.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] If one then wanted to listen to the lead vocals in isolation, one would do so by muting all the tracks apart from the lead vocals track.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] If one wanted to listen to the entire song, one could do so by unmuting all the tracks.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] If one did not like the guitar part, or found a mistake in it, and wanted to replace it, one could do so by re-recording *only* the guitar part (i.e., re-recording only the track on which the guitar was recorded), rather than re-recording the entire song.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] If all the voices and instruments in a recording are individually recorded on distinct tracks, then the artist is able to retain complete control over the final sculpting of the song during the mix-down (re-recording to two stereo tracks for mass distribution) phase.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] However, if they had been recorded onto separate tracks, then the artist could blend and alter all of the instrument and vocal sounds with complete freedom.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Multitracking a song also leaves open the possibilities of remixes by the same or future artists, such as DJs.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] If the song was not available in a multitrack format recording, the job of the remixing artist was very difficult, or impossible, because, once the tracks had been re-recorded together onto a single track ('mixed down'), they were previously considered inseparable.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] More recent software allows sound source separation, whereby individual instruments, voices and effects can be *upmixed* — isolated from a single-track source — in high quality.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] This has permitted the production of stereophonic or surround sound mixes of recordings that were originally mastered and released in mono.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] The process was conceived and developed by Ross Snyder at Ampex in 1955, resulting in the first Sel-Sync machine, an 8-track machine which used one-inch tape.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] This 8-track recorder was sold to the American guitarist, songwriter, luthier, and inventor Les Paul for $10,000.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Les Paul, Mary Ford and Patti Page used the technology in the late 1950s to enhance vocals and instruments.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] From these beginnings, it evolved in subsequent decades into a mainstream recording technique.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Professional multitrack analog audio tape manufacturers included Ampex, EMI, MCI, Otari, Scully, Soundcraft, Stephens, Studer, TASCAM, 3M (Mincom division).
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Since the early 1990s, many performers have recorded music using only a Mac or PC equipped with multitrack recording software as a tracking machine.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] The computer must have a sound card or other type of audio interface with one or more Analog-to-digital converters.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Microphones are needed to record the sounds of vocalists or acoustic instruments.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Depending on the capabilities of the system, some instruments, such as a synthesizer or electric guitar, can also be sent to an interface directly using Line level or MIDI inputs.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Direct inputs eliminate the need for microphones and can provide another range of sound control options.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] There are tremendous differences in computer audio interfaces.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Such units vary widely in price, sound quality, and flexibility.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] The most basic interfaces use audio circuitry that is built into the computer motherboard.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] The most sophisticated audio interfaces are external units of professional studio quality, which can cost thousands of dollars.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Professional interfaces usually use one or more IEEE 1394 (commonly known as FireWire) connections.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Other types of interfaces may use internal PCI cards, or external USB connections.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Popular manufacturers of high-quality interfaces include Apogee Electronics, Avid Audio (formerly Digidesign), Echo Digital Audio, Focusrite, Solid State Logic, MOTU, RME Audio, M-Audio and PreSonus.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Microphones are often designed for highly specific applications and have a major effect on recording quality.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] A single studio-quality microphone can cost $5,000 or more, while consumer-quality recording microphones can be bought for less than $50 each.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Microphones also need some type of microphone preamplifier to prepare the signal for use by other equipment.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] These preamplifiers can also have a major effect on the sound and come in different price ranges, physical configurations, and capability levels.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Microphone preamplifiers may be external units or a built-in feature of other audio equipment.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Software for multitrack recording can record multiple tracks at once.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] It generally uses graphic notation for an interface and offers a number of views of the music.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Most multitrackers also provide audio playback capability.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Some multitrack software also provides MIDI playback functions not just for audio; during playback, the MIDI data is sent to a softsynth or virtual instrument (e.g., VSTi) which converts the data to audio sound.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Multitrack software may also provide other features that qualify it as a digital audio workstation (DAW).
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] These features may include various displays, including showing the score of the music, as well as editing capability.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] There is often overlap between many of the categories of musical software.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] In this case, scorewriters and full-featured multitrackers such as DAWs have similar features for playback but may have less similarity for editing and recording.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Multitrack recording software varies widely in price and capability.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Popular multitrack recording software programs include: Reason, Ableton Live, FL Studio, Adobe Audition, Pro Tools, Digital Performer, Cakewalk Sonar, Samplitude, Nuendo, Cubase and Logic.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Lower-cost alternatives include Mixcraft, REAPER and n-Track Studio.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Open-source and free software programs are also available for multitrack recording.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] These range from very basic programs such as Jokosher to Ardour and Audacity, which are capable of performing many functions of the most sophisticated programs.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Instruments and voices are usually recorded as individual files on a computer hard drive.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] These function as tracks which can be added, removed or processed in many ways.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Effects such as reverb, chorus, and delays can be applied by electronic devices or by computer software.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Such effects are used to shape the sound as desired by the producer.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] When the producer is satisfied with the recorded sound, finished tracks can be mixed into a new stereo pair of tracks within the multitrack recording software.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Finally, the final stereo recording can be written to a CD, which can be copied and distributed.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] In modern popular songs, drums, percussion instruments and electric bass are often among the first instruments to be recorded.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] These are the core instruments of the rhythm section.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Musicians recording later tracks use the precise attack of the drum sounds as a rhythmic guide.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] In some styles, the drums may be recorded for a few bars and then looped.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Click (metronome) tracks are also often used as the first sound to be recorded, especially when the drummer is not available for the initial recording, and/or the final mix will be synchronized with motion picture and/or video images.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] One reason that a band may start with just the drums is that this allows the band to pick the song's key later on.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] The producer and the musicians can experiment with the song's key and arrangement against the basic rhythm track.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Also, though the drums might eventually be mixed down to a couple of tracks, each individual drum and percussion instrument might be initially recorded to its own individual track.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] The drums and percussion combined can occupy a large number of tracks utilized in a recording.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] This is done so that each percussion instrument can be processed individually for maximum effect.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Equalization is often used on individual drums to bring out each one's characteristic sound.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] The last tracks recorded are often the vocals (though a temporary vocal track may be recorded early on, either as a reference or to guide subsequent musicians; this is sometimes called a *guide vocal*, *ghost vocal* or *scratch vocal*).
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] One reason for this is that singers will often temper their vocal expression in accordance with the accompaniment.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Producers and songwriters can also use the guide/scratch vocal when they have not quite ironed out all the lyrics or for flexibility based on who sings the lead vocal (as The Alan Parsons Project's Eric Woolfson often did).
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] For classical and jazz recordings, particularly instrumentals where multitracking is chosen as the recording method (as opposed to direct to stereo, for example), a different arrangement is used; all tracks are recorded simultaneously.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Sound barriers are often placed between different groups within the orchestra, e.g. pianists, violinists, percussionists, etc.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] When barriers are used, these groups listen to each other via headphones.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Multitrack live recording is a lot like gigging – a lot of planning ahead of time, a lot of gear to carry and set up, a lot of waiting, and then a lot of hectic activity over the next 40 minutes or so.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] There is little doubt that a pseudolive studio performance can enhance certain forms of music, particularly those with a lot of intensity in the live performance, but it still lacks the atmosphere of a real gig.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] You may record the moment with a portable setup during the performance.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] You can produce wonderful live recordings with just two microphones and a building's inherent acoustics, but that will have to wait for another day.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Taking a feed from the front of house (or FOH) desk directly to tape or DAT is another technique of live recording, although this will only work in large venues where everything is run through the PA system.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] Even so, a loud backline will result in less guitar and bass being routed via the main PA system, resulting in an unbalanced mix.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] A multitrack recording has distinct advantages: it allows you more control after the event because you may fine-tune the mix and correct any obvious mistakes without sacrificing the thrill of the live performance.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/multitrack-recording] It does, however, necessitate a lot more pre-gig planning as well as a lot more equipment.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] VST plugins generally run within a digital audio workstation (DAW), to provide additional functionality, though a few standalone plugin hosts exist that support VST.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] Most VST plugins are either instruments (VSTi) or effects (VSTfx), although other categories exist—for example spectrum analyzers and various meters.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] VST plugins usually provide a custom graphical user interface that displays controls similar to physical switches and knobs on audio hardware.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] Some (often older) plugins rely on the host application for their user interface.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] VST instruments include software simulation emulations of well-known hardware synthesizers and samplers.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] These typically emulate the look of the original equipment as well as its sonic characteristics.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] This lets musicians and recording engineers use virtual versions of devices that otherwise might be difficult and expensive to obtain.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] VST instruments receive notes as digital information via MIDI, and output digital audio.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] Effect plugins receive digital audio and process it through to their outputs.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] (Some effect plugins also accept MIDI input—for example, MIDI sync to modulate the effect in sync with the tempo).
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] MIDI messages can control both instrument and effect plugin parameters.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] Most host applications can route the audio output from one VST to the audio input of another VST (*chaining*).
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] For example, the output of a VST synthesizer can be sent through a VST reverb effect.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] Steinberg released the VST interface specification and SDK in 1996.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] They released it at the same time as Steinberg Cubase 3.02, which included the first VST format plugins: Espacial (a reverb), Choirus (a chorus effect), Stereo Echo, and Auto-Panner.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] Steinberg updated the VST interface specification to version 2.0 in 1999.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] One addition was the ability for plugins to receive MIDI data.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] This supported the introduction of *Virtual Studio Technology Instrument (VSTi)* format plugins.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] VST Instruments can act as standalone software synthesizers, samplers, or drum machines.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] Neon was the first available VST Instrument (included with Cubase VST 3.7).
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] It was a 16-voice, 2-oscillator virtual analog synthesizer.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] In 2006, the VST interface specification was updated to version 2.4.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] Changes included the ability to process audio with 64-bit precision.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] A free-software replacement was developed for LMMS that would be used later by other free-software projects.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] Changes included *note expression*, which provides extensive articulation information in individual note events in a polyphonic arrangement.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] According to Steinberg, this supports performance flexibility and a more natural playing feel.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] In October 2011, Celemony Software and PreSonus released Audio Random Access (ARA), an extension for audio plug-in interfaces, such as VST, allowing greater integration between audio plug-ins and DAW software.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] In September, 2013, Steinberg discontinued maintenance of the VST 2 SDK.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] In December, Steinberg stopped distributing the SDK.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] It includes a preview version of VST3 for Linux platform, the VST3 part of the SDK gets a dual license: "Proprietary Steinberg VST3" or the "Open-source GPLv3".
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] VST 3.8.0, released in October 2025, changed the licensing to open source under an MIT license.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] A VST host is a software application or hardware device that VST plugins run under.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] The host application presents the plugin UIs and routes digital audio and MIDI to and from the plugins.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] Examples of VST hosts include media players such as JRiver Media Center and foobar2000.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] Stand-alone *dedicated hosts* provide a host environment for VST plugins rather than use the plugins to extend their own capabilities.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] These are usually optimized for live performance use, with features like fast song configuration switching.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] VST plugins can be hosted in incompatible environments using a translation layer, or shim.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] For example, FL Studio only supports its own internal plugin architecture, but an available native "wrapper" loads VST plugins, among others.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] FXpansion offers a VST-to-RTAS (Real Time AudioSuite) wrapper that lets VST plugins run in Pro Tools, and a VST-to-Audio Units wrapper lets VST plugins run in Logic Pro.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] Hardware VST hosts can load special versions of VST plugins.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] These units are portable and usable without a computer, though some of them require a computer for editing.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] Other hardware options include PCI/PCIe cards designed for audio processing, which take over audio processing from the computer's CPU and free up RAM.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] Some hardware hosts accept VSTs and VSTis, and either run Windows-compatible music applications like Cubase, Live, Pro Tools, Logic etc., or run their own DAW.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] Other are VST Hosts only and require a separate DAW application.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] *Origin* from Arturia is a hardware DSP system that houses several VST software synthesizers in one machine, like Jupiter 50/80 from Roland.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] Using appropriate software, audio data can also be sent over a network, so the main host runs on one computer, and VST plugins on peripheral machines.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] The VST plugin standard is the audio plugin standard created by Steinberg to allow any third-party developers to create VST plugins for use within VST host applications.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] VST requires separate installations for Windows, macOS, and Linux.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] The short history of commercial environments for Linux means few developers have targeted this platform.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] VST plugins often have many controls, and therefore need a method of managing presets (sets of control settings).
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] Steinberg Cubase VST introduced two file formats for storing presets: an FXP file stores a single preset, while an FXB file stores a whole bank of presets.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] These formats have since been adopted by many other VST hosts, although Cubase itself switched to a new system of preset management with Cubase 4.0.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] Many VST plugins have their own method of loading and saving presets, which do not necessarily use the standard FXP/FXB formats.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] Steinberg's VST SDK is a set of C++ classes based around an underlying C API.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] The SDK can be downloaded from their website.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] In addition, Steinberg has developed the VST GUI, which is another set of C++ classes, which can be used to build a graphical interface.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] There are classes for buttons, sliders and displays, etc.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] Note that these are low-level C++ classes and the look and feel still have to be created by the plugin manufacturer.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] VST GUI is part of the VST SDK and is also available as a SourceForge project.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] There are also several ports to other programming languages available from third parties.
[src:digital-audio-workstation/virtual-studio-technology] Many commercial and open-source VSTs are written using the Juce C++ framework instead of direct calls to the VST SDK because this allows multi-format (VST, Audio Units and Real Time AudioSuite) binaries to be built from a single codebase.
